Public Prosecutor v Mohd Raman Bin Daud
[2022] SGDC 296

Case Number:District Arrest Case No 907431-2022, Magistrate's Appeal No 9243-2022-01
Decision Date:12 December 2022
Tribunal/Court:District Court
Coram: Salina Bte Ishak
Counsel Name(s): Sruthi Boppana (Attorney-General's Chambers) for the Prosecution; Mohamed Muzammil Bin Mohamed (Muzammil & Co) for the accused.
Parties: Public Prosecutor — Mohd Raman bin Daud

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act – Driving without due care and attention and causing hurt

[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9243/2022/01.]

12 December 2022

District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

Background

1       The accused, Mr Mohd Raman Bin Daud, a 65-year-old male Singapore citizen had pleaded guilty to the following amended charge:

Amended Charge

are charged that on 9 December 2021 at or about 2.57 p.m., along Block 34A Bedok South Avenue 2 carpark service road exit towards Bedok South Avenue 2 Singapore, did drive motorcar SMC1438U on a road without due care and attention, to wit, by failing stop before the stop line and continuing to travel towards Bedok South Avenue 2 and failing to keep a proper lookout when making a left turn out from the carpark service road exit of Block 34A Bedok South Avenue 2 into Bedok South Avenue 2, thereby colliding into Teo Kee Cheng, male / 72 years old who was cycling along Bedok South Avenue 2, from your right to left across the carpark exit, causing him to sustain hurt, inter alia, a left distal tibia fibula open fracture, a right index finger laceration with tendon exposure, resulting in him being warded for at least 43 days, and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(a) punishable under Section 65(4)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed).

2       The accused was originally charged with an offence of driving without due care and attention and causing grievous hurt to the said cyclist Mr Teo Kee Cheng under s 65(3)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”). On condition of a plea of guilt, the Prosecution agreed to proceed on a reduced charge of driving without due care and attention and causing hurt under s 65(4)(a) of the RTA.

3       On 28 November 2022, the accused pleaded guilty to the amended charge (C1A) and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification. After carefully considering the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence and the accused’s plea in mitigation, I imposed a sentence of four weeks’ imprisonment and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of 18 months with effect from the date of release. The accused sought a deferment of sentence until 6 December 2022 to enable him to attend a medical examination at the Changi General Hospital on 5 December 2022.

4       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed his Notice of Appeal against my sentence and order of disqualification through his new Defence Counsel Mr Noor Mohamed Marican (Marican & Associates) on 2 December 2022. He is currently on bail pending the hearing of his appeal.

5       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

Salient Facts

6       The accused was the driver of motorcar bearing vehicle registration number SMC1438U (“the car”). The victim is Teo Kee Cheng, male / 72 years old. At the material time, he was riding his bicycle.

First Incident Report

7       On 9 December 2021 at about 3.03pm, the accused called the police to inform “PLEASE COME QUICKLY. I KNOCKED DOWN AN OLD MAN ON BICYCLE.” The incident location was reported as being along Bedok South Ave 2 towards Bedok South Road at the carpark entrance/exit of Block 34A Bedok South Avenue 2.

Facts pertaining to the charge

8       On 9 December 2021 at or about 2.57pm, the accused was driving the car out of a multi-storey carpark near Block 34A Bedok South Avenue 2, out of the carpark service road exit towards Bedok South Avenue 2 Singapore. Upon reaching the exit of the said service road, and before making a left turn towards Bedok South Avenue 2, the accused drove without due care and attention, by failing to stop at the end of the service road and keep a proper lookout for oncoming traffic before making a left turn. At this juncture, the victim was riding his bicycle along Bedok South Avenue 2, from the accused’s right to left perspective across the carpark exit. As a result, the accused’s car collided into the victim, causing the victim to fall off his bicycle and onto the road. The said incident was captured by the accused’s in-car cameras.

9       The accused’s in-car camera footage revealed that he was travelling along Block 34A Bedok South Avenue 2 carpark service road towards the exit. He did not stop before the stop line and continued to travel towards the main road of Bedok South Avenue 2. At this point, the victim was seen cycling slowly along the main road of Bedok South Avenue 2 towards Bedok South Road on lane 2 of the 2-lane road and had passed by half of the carpark entrance/exit, in plain view.

10     The accused then made the left turn onto Bedok South Avenue 2 and collided into the victim whilst doing so. The accused’s car then ran over the victim’s bicycle and the rear-view camera captured the victim lying down on the road with his bicycle over him. The accused stopped the car and attended to the victim.

11     At the time of accident, the weather was fine, road surface was dry and traffic volume was light.

12     As a result of the accident, the victim’s bicycle sustained the following damages as per the vehicle damage report:

(a)     Right handlebar was ripped off;

(b)     Front wheel twisted;

(c)     Right side pedal dented;

(d)     Scratches over the rear right wheel. 8.

As a result of the accident, the car sustained scratches and dents over the front right portion.

Injuries

13     The victim was conveyed by ambulance to Changi General Hospital (“CGH”) from the scene. The medical report obtained from CGH dated 8 February 2022 states that the victim sustained the following injuries as a result of the accused’s acts:

(a)     Left distal tibia fibula open fracture; and

(b)     Right index finger proximal interphalangeal joint (PIPJ) laceration with tendon exposure.

14     The victim underwent debridement and surgical fixation of the left tibia open fracture and debridement of the right index finger on 9 December 2021. The victim was hospitalised at CGH from 9 to 21 December 2021, for a period of 13 days. The victim was then transferred to Saint Andrew’s Community Hospital on 21 December 2021 and was subsequently discharged on 20 January 2022. He was hospitalised for a total period of 43 days. The victim underwent physiotherapy and occupational therapy. No further hospitalisation leave was sought upon his discharge as the victim is a retiree. The victim informed that he still feels pain on his leg and has a follow-up appointment scheduled on 15 December 2022.

Conclusion

15     By virtue of the foregoing, the accused has committed the offence of Driving without due care and attention thereby causing hurt, under Section 65(1)(a) punishable under Section 65(4)(a) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276.

Sentencing

Prescribed Penalty

16     The prescribed penalty for an offence of driving without due care and attention and causing hurt under s 65(1)(a) punishable under s 65(4)(a) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”) is fine not exceeding $2,500 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or to both.

17     In addition, s 42(1) of the RTA provides that a court before which person convicted of an offence in connection with the driving of a motor vehicle, may in addition to the punishment provided for the offence, order him to be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for life or for any period as the court may think fit.

Antecedents

18     The accused had compounded the following speeding offences:

(a)     On 3 July 1990 for $70 where he had exceeded the speed limit by 21-30km/h;

(b)     On 3 September 2012 for $130 where he had exceeded the speed limit by 1-20 km/h;

(c)     On 3 May 2013 for $130 where he had exceeded the speed limit by 1-20 km/h.

Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

19     The Prosecution had urged the Court to impose a term of at least four weeks’ imprisonment and disqualification for 18 months for all classes of vehicles. It was submitted that having regard to the entire sentencing range stipulated in s 65(4)(a) of the RTA and based on the guidance provided in Sue Chang (Xu Zheng) v Public Prosecutor [2022] SGHC 176 (“Sue Chang”) (albeit in the context of offences punishable under s 65(3)(a) of the RTA), the sentencing range of a fine or up to two months’ imprisonment would be applicable.

Culpability

20     On the present facts, it was the Prosecution’s case that the accused’s culpability is low to moderate for the following reasons:

(a)     The accused failed to stop at the Stop-line when moving out of the carpark onto the main road;

(b)     The victim was proceeding slowly, right in front of the accused’s car from his right to left, and would have been clearly within the accused’s line of sight – if he had kept a proper look out; and

(c)     The accused stopped to render assistance shortly after the collision had occurred.

Harm

21     It was submitted that in considering the harm caused, it is evident that where fractures result, these would ordinarily fall within the category of at least moderate, especially given that s 65(4)(a) RTA targets cases where simple hurt results.

22     On the present facts, the victim suffered a left distal tibia fibula open fracture that required surgical fixation and a right index finger proximal interphalangeal joint (PIPJ) laceration with tendon exposure. The victim was hospitalised for at least 43 days and was unable to engage in his ordinary pursuits for this period. He required physiotherapy and occupational therapy.

23     It was noted that the prescribed sentencing ranges are applicable to cases whereby the accused claims trial to their charge(s). With due regard to the accused’s plea of guilt in the present case, albeit in the face of clear evidence from his in-car camera footages, it was submitted that a term of at least four weeks’ imprisonment together with an 18-month disqualification would duly reflect his culpability and the resultant harm to the victim in the present case. It was highlighted that the victim is pursuing a civil claim separately in relation to the medical costs incurred, no restitution has been made by the accused thus far.

Defence’s Submissions on Sentence

24     The Defence Counsel, Mr Mohamed Muzammil Bin Mohamed (Muzammil & Co) had sought the imposition of the heaviest fine and the shortest period of disqualification. In his plea in mitigation, the Defence had set out the accused’s background, his personal circumstances as well as the events leading to the accident.

25     At the material time, the accused and his wife had left their home at about 2:45pm to attend to routine congregational prayers. The collision had occurred while the accused was driving along the service road of Block 34A Bedok South Avenue 2. Although the accused had driven slowly, due to a momentary lapse of care and attention, he had collided into the victim who was cycling from the accused’s right to left. The accused is extremely sorry for causing the accident which led to the victim suffering personal injuries.

26     In the plea mitigation, the Defence had highlighted the following factors:

(a)     This was the first time the accused had been charged with an offence under the RTA after holding a driving licence of 39 years with the exception of minor traffic violations;

(b)     By pleading guilty, the accused had saved the Court’s time and resources as well as inconvenience to the Prosecution’s witnesses including the victim who was 72 years’ old at the time of the offence as well as the doctors from the two hospitals;

(c)     After the collision, the accused had rendered immediate assistance to the victim by carrying the victim to the side of the road while his wife called for the ambulance;

(d)     He had readily handed his SIM card from his in-car camera to the police to assist them in their investigations;

(e)     He urged the Court to give due consideration of his public service to the Government and the community of Singapore in the field of Malay language, literature and culture in Singapore.

Submissions on sentence

Culpability

27     It was submitted that it could be seen from the footage that the accused was driving slowly along the service road of the carpark. The victim would have also seen the accused approaching the junction if he had been more attentive. It was further submitted that there was no blind spot for either of them. It was the Defence’s position that the accused’s culpability was low and the victim’s lack of care and attention to the presence of the accused’s motorcar would have lessened the accused’s culpability. It was highlighted that the accused’s lapse of care and attention was momentary.

Harm

28     It was further submitted that the harm was at the lower end of moderate as the victim had fully recovered from his injuries or almost fully recovered as he was on the road to recovery.

29     The Defence urged the Court to tamper justice with mercy and that the offence he committed would leave a black mark to his record of illustrious and dedicated public service to Singapore and the community.

Prosecution’s Reply

30     In response to the plea in mitigation, the Prosecution submitted that the accident was not something that the victim could be blamed for given that he was on the main road.

31     It was further submitted that the accused holds responsibility for the accident and in any event, even if the victim had contributed in some way, this is not something that reduces the accused’s culpability in any manner. However, on the facts of the present case, it cannot be said that the victim had contributed to the accident.

Decision on sentence

Sentencing approach

32     S 65(1) of the RTA encapsulates the primary offence of driving without due care or reasonable consideration for other persons using the road. The subsequent subsections from ss 65(2) to 65(4) are the penalty prescribing provisions, each tiered according to the degree of hurt caused and for s 65(5), for any other case of non-personal injury or potential harm.

Irresponsible driving under the Road Traffic Act

33     The present offence of driving without due care and attention under s 65(1)(a) of the RTA was enacted on 1 November 2019, following the passing of the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019). The Amendment Act arose out of a review of the RTA and it aimed to provide stronger deterrence against irresponsible driving.

34     As at the date of my decision, there is no existing sentencing framework enunciated by the High Court for an offence driving without due care and attention and causing hurt punishable under s 65(4)(a) of the RTA. As submitted by the Prosecution, there is however a sentencing framework for an offence of driving without due care and attention and causing grievous hurt punishable under s 65(3)(a) of the RTA prescribed by Vincent Hoong J (“Hoong J”) in Sue Chang. In that case, Hoong J had dismissed the appeal and prescribed the following sentencing framework for offences under section 65(3)(a) of the RTA where the offender has claimed trial.

 

35     In Sue Chang, Hoong J made to two key observations at [38] to [40] in relation to the RTA amendments in the context of careless or inconsiderate driving. Firstly, as observed by Sundaresh Menon CJ (“Menon CJ”) in Wu Zhi Yong v Public Prosecutor [2022] 4 SLR 587 (“Wu Zhi Yong”) at [15] (albeit in the related context of s 64 of the RTA), the Amendment Act envisaged a new scheme of penalties for careless or inconsiderate driving in a tiered structure calibrated according to the degree of hurt caused. This is codified in the RTA as ss 65(2) to 65(5). The maximum punishments which may be imposed for each category of harm increase concomitantly with the seriousness of the harm caused; this translates into wider ranges of punishments where more serious harm is occasioned. For instance, where death is caused, s 65(2)(a) provides that a first-time offender is liable to a fine not exceeding $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding three years or to both. In contrast, the residual category (where no actual physical harm is caused, but which includes cases of non-personal injury or potential harm) captured in s 65(5)(a) provides that a first-time offender is liable to a fine not exceeding $1,500 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months or to both. By tiering the punishment provisions in accordance with the type of harm suffered, Parliament has given clear expression to the need to give explicit consideration to the outcomes that result from instances of careless or inconsiderate driving. This is a stark departure from the structure of s 65 of the pre-2019 RTA, where there was a single range of punishment with no differentiation based on the type and/or degree of harm caused.

36     Secondly, while Parliament has retained the distinction between reckless or dangerous driving under s 64 of the RTA and careless or inconsiderate driving under s 65 of the RTA, this distinction has been made more pronounced through the refining of the punishment provisions. These two provisions reflect the differing circumstances under which an irresponsible driving offence can occur. Accordingly, the current architecture of the RTA concerning irresponsible driving offences tiers the punishment provisions according to both harm and culpability, not dissimilar to the Penal Code.

37     At [65] of his judgment, Hoong J opined that the most suitable sentencing approach to adopt in respect of offences under s 65(3)(a) of the RTA is the two-stage, five-step sentencing framework laid down by Menon CJ in Logachev Vladislav v PP [2018] 4 SLR 609 at [75](“Logachev-hybrid approach”). At [84] to [108] of his judgment, Hoong J had set out the five steps to be taken namely:

(a)     The first step is to identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender. The harm caused by the offence may be categorised into three levels of increasing severity: low, moderate and serious. Likewise, the offender’s culpability may be categorised into three levels: low, moderate and high. The non-exhaustive list of factors within the broad categories of harm and culpability which fashion the two axes of the matrix are:

1)        Factors going to harm

The degree of harm caused would generally refer to the nature and degree of the grievous bodily injury caused to the victim(s): see Tang Ling Lee v PP [2018] 4 SLR 813 at [25] (“Tang Ling Lee”). The levels of harm can be divided based on the severity of the grievous hurt suffered as follows:

(i)        Low: The hurt caused can be managed with conservative treatment, with no or short periods of hospitalisation and/or medical leave. The harm occasioned would typically involve minor fractures/dislocation at less vulnerable parts of the body.

(ii)        Moderate: The injuries are of a more permanent nature and/or involve more complex fractures/dislocation which necessitate some surgical procedures with a moderate period of hospitalisation and/or medical leave.

(iii)        Serious: The injuries are of a very serious or permanent nature and/or necessitate significant surgical procedures. The victim’s daily living is usually permanently and severely affected. This includes injuries resulting in loss of limb, sight, hearing, member or other major bodily functions or paralysis.

In addition, there are two other factors which may contribute to the severity of the harm caused, namely: (a) property damage; and (b) potential harm. These factors are to be considered in tandem with the above descriptions of each level of harm.

2)        Factors going to culpability

This can be measured based on the following factors:

(a)       Circumstances which required the offender to exercise extra care or consideration. Some examples of these circumstances include where the offender drives: (i) within a school or residential zone; (ii) a heavy vehicle that is more difficult to control and requires a quicker reaction time; or (iii) in poor road conditions (eg, heavy rain or heavy traffic);

(b)       The manner of driving. Under this factor, it is apposite to consider any dangerous driving behaviour exhibited by the offender. This would include, for example, driving against the flow of traffic, speeding, sleepy driving, drink-driving, driving while under the influence of drugs, driving while using a mobile phone, flouting traffic rules, or “hell-riding” situations: see Tang Ling Lee at [28]. In addition, considerations pertaining to the duration of the offender’s inattention (eg, momentary or prolonged/sustained), the avoidability of the offender’s distraction or the reasonableness of the offender’s misjudgement are also relevant;

(c)       The offender’s conduct following the offence. An offender’s conduct that is “belligerent or violent” upon arrest would constitute an aggravating factor: see Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor [2013] 4 SLR 1139 (“Suse Nathen”) at [32]. Where the offender fails to stop in an attempt to evade arrest or to avoid apprehension by the authorities, this should also weigh against him: see Public Prosecutor v Lee Meng Soon [2007] 4 SLR(R) 240 at [33].

(b)     The second step is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix. Any term of imprisonment imposed may be accompanied by a fine of up to $5,000, if appropriate as this is explicitly provided for in s 65(3)(a) of the RTA. The sentencing judge should be alive to possibility of imposing such a combination of punishments in order to properly take into account the full sentencing range prescribed by Parliament. Hoong J opined that Parliament has stressed the importance of both harm and culpability and did not suggest that one factor should be given more weight in the sentencing analysis than the other. He emphasized that the proposed sentencing framework and the corresponding indicative ranges set out above are concerned solely with section 65(3)(a) of the RTA.

(c)     The third step is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. This is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability.

(d)     The fourth step is to make adjustments to the starting point where necessary to take into account the offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors: see Ng Kean Meng Terence v Public Prosecutor [2017] 2 SLR 449 (“Terence Ng”) at [62]-[71].

(e)     The fifth step is to make further adjustments to take into account the totality principle. This step is relevant only where an offender is faced with multiple charges. It requires the court to consider the need to make further adjustments to the individual sentences for each charge to take into account the totality principle. The totality principle has been expressed in Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v Public Prosecutor [2014] 2 SLR 998 at [54] and [57] as comprising two limbs. The first limb examines whether the aggregate sentence is substantially above the normal level of sentences for the most serious of the individual offences committed. The second limb considers whether the effect of the sentence on the offender is crushing and not in keeping with his past record and his future prospects.

38     Although the present case concerns a charge of driving without due care and attention and causing hurt, as both statutory provisions relate to the prescribed penalties for irresponsible driving under s 65(1), I was of the view the observations as well as the sentencing approach set out by Hoong J provides some useful guidance on how an offence punishable under s 65(4)(a) of the RTA should be dealt with.

The sentence

39     I now turn to the facts of the present case and the application of the above sentencing framework.

40     The first step is to identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender. In the present case, I was of the view that the level of harm was within the moderate range as the victim suffered a left distal tibia fibula (ie the two long bones in the lower leg) open fracture that required surgical fixation and a right index finger proximal interphalangeal joint laceration with tendon exposure. The victim was hospitalised for substantial period of at least 43 days and was unable to engage in his ordinary pursuits for this period. He required physiotherapy and occupational therapy. He was not given any hospitalisation leave as he is a retiree. The victim still feels pain on his leg and has a follow-up appointment scheduled on 15 December 2022. Given these facts, I disagreed with the Defence that the victim has fully recovered or almost fully recovered and that the harm caused as being at the lower end of moderate.

41     As for the accused’s level of culpability, I was of the view that it was at the higher end of low as the accused failed to stop at the Stop line to check for oncoming traffic along Bedok South Avenue 2 before he made a left turn onto the main road. Paragraph 70 of the Highway Code provides:

70.     When approaching a junction with a major road, slow down gradually and give way to traffic on the major road. Where there is a “STOP” sign, stop at the major road.

42     If the accused had been attentive to the traffic along the main road, looked ahead, kept a proper look out as he was approaching the Stop line and stopped at the Stop-line, he would have noticed the 72-year-old victim who is considered as a vulnerable person, cycling slowly along Bedok South Avenue 2 as the victim was within his line of sight. This is particularly so as both the accused and the victim had been proceeding slowly.

43     I disagreed with the Defence that the victim bears some responsibility for the accident as the victim who was cycling on the main road had the right of way. Paragraph 69A(c) of the Highway Code provides that if a motorist is turning left, he must give way to traffic from the right.

Paragraph 69A(c) Highway Code

44     The second step is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix. Any term of imprisonment imposed may be accompanied by a fine of up to $2,500, if appropriate as this is explicitly provided for in s 65(4)(a) of the RTA. The sentencing judge should be alive to possibility of imposing such a combination of punishments in order to properly take into account the full sentencing range prescribed by Parliament. Based on the Sue Chang sentencing framework where the level of culpability is at the higher end of low and the harm moderate, the appropriate range of sentence would be a fine or a custodial sentence.

45     In the present case, I agreed with the Prosecution that the custodial threshold had been crossed. This is in view of the seriousness of the harm caused which resulted in the victim suffering a left distal tibia fibula open fracture that required surgical fixation and a right index finger proximal interphalangeal joint laceration with tendon exposure. The victim was hospitalised for substantial period of at least 43 days and was unable to engage in his ordinary pursuits for this period. The victim continues to feel pain in his leg.

46     The third step is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. This is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability. In the present case, in view of the degree of harm caused, I was of the view that the starting point should be a custodial period of two months.

47     The fourth step is to make adjustments to the starting point where necessary to take into account the offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors. In the present case, I considered the fact that the accused had pleaded guilty to the charge, he had rendered immediate assistance to the victim, he had cooperated with the authorities and had a dated driving history. I further considered that there were no culpability enhancing factors in the present case. Accordingly, I was of the view that a downward calibration to four weeks’ imprisonment was warranted in view of these mitigating factors.

48     I disagreed with the Defence’s position that a high fine was appropriate in view of the seriousness of the harm caused as set out above which required not only surgical fixation as well as a lengthy period of hospitalisation, but the victim also underwent physiotherapy and occupational therapy to aid in his recovery.

49     I did not place much weight to the Defence’s submissions on the accused’s public service contribution in the field of Malay language, literature and culture in Singapore. In Stansilas Fabian Kester v Public Prosecutor [2017] 5 SLR 755 at [101], the Honourable Sundaresh Menon CJ held that in order for the rehabilitative reasoning to apply in sentencing, the offender must satisfy the court that the evidence of his contributions to the public is also indicative of his willingness to change for the better. Even then, save in the limited case of young offenders, this will have limited weight. This is because the sentencing objectives of punishment, protection of the public and deterrence are of greater importance.

50     The fifth step was not applicable in the present case as the accused faced a single charge.

Disqualification order

51     In deciding on the appropriate period of disqualification, I was mindful that the disqualification order and the sentence imposed are not mutually compensatory; an increase in the quantum of the fine imposed should not be taken to mandate the imposition of a reduced period of disqualification than would otherwise have been ordered: Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor [2013] 4 SLR 1139 at [13].

52     In determining the appropriate length of the disqualification order, I was guided by the approach in the recent case of Kwan Weiguang v Public Prosecutor [2022] SGHC 121 (“Kwan”). Although Aedit Abdullah J dealt with an appeal against a disqualification order of 15 months that was imposed on the appellant for an offence of dangerous driving under s 64(1) and punishable under s 64(2C)(a) of the RTA, the factors considered are relevant to the present case. He held at [59] and [61] that the objective of the disqualification order is as follow:

A driving disqualification order combines three sentencing objectives: punishment, protection of the public and deterrence (Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor [2013] 4 SLR 1139 (“Edwin Nathen”) at [13]). Often, due to the limited range of fines in the punishment provision, the impact of a disqualification order is likely to be felt much more acutely than any marginal increase in the quantum of the fine (see Edwin Nathen at [13])…

61    A disqualification order also serves to remove the privilege to drive from those who have abused it, and this also reinforces the notion of shared usage of the roads. It must be remembered that driving is an inherently dangerous activity. The licence to drive is a privilege accorded to persons who, through a series of properly administered tests, have demonstrated that they are capable of meeting the standards expected of a reasonably competent driver (Jali bin Mohd Yunos v Public Prosecutor [2014] 4 SLR 1059 at [36]). The former Minister for Home Affairs, Prof S Jayakumar, had expressed the following view which reinforces this notion (see Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report (28 March 1990) vol 55 at col 960): “… we must get every driver in Singapore to note that when he is issued a licence, it is in fact a very special privilege and it is granted on condition that he drives in a responsible manner bearing in mind the interest of others.”

53     In Kwan at [65] to [71], the relevant and material factors when determining the period of disqualification are:

(a)     Circumstances of the commission of the offence;

(b)     Continued ability to drive and attitude towards other road users.

54     In the present case, the accused had failed to stop at the Stop line to check for oncoming traffic along the main road before he made a left turn onto Bedok South Avenue 2 and collided into the victim whilst doing so. The accused’s car then ran over the victim’s bicycle and the rear-view camera of the accused’s car captured the victim lying down on the road with his bicycle over him. The accused had failed to keep a proper lookout ahead despite the fact that the victim, an elderly man could be seen cycling slowly along on the main road from the accused’s right in the front view in-car footage.

55     In addition, there was a fair degree of potential harm, considering the conditions at the material time. Although the traffic volume was described in the Statement of Facts as light, it was evident from the footage that the road traffic was not negligible. The offence occurred at about at about 2.57pm along Bedok South Avenue 2 when there was still some traffic, and this is unlike the situation in Neo Chuan Sheng v Public Prosecutor [2020] SGHC 97 where the offence was committed at about 2.10am when no vehicles or pedestrians would be expected to be on the road. It is foreseeable that as the accused made the left turn without checking for oncoming traffic from his right after exiting the service road onto the main road, he could have caused a collision with other road users travelling along Bedok South Avenue 2.

56     It was clear that in the present case it was within the public’s interest to remove such a driver from the roads for a substantial period of time. Based on the above factors, the shortest period of disqualification sought by the Defence was wholly inappropriate in the circumstances. Under such circumstances, a disqualification period of higher than 12 months was warranted. In my view, taking all the above circumstances into account, a disqualification period of eighteen months for all classes of vehicles was appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public and deterrence.

57     All things considered, I was of the view that the sentence of four weeks’ imprisonment and a disqualification from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of eighteen months in respect of DAC 907431-2022 was just and appropriate in the circumstances.
